update public.learn_articles
set content = 'There is a moment in the Chandogya Upanishad that has stopped readers in their tracks for nearly three thousand years. A father named Uddalaka is teaching his son Shvetaketu about the ultimate nature of reality. He asks his son to fetch a fruit from the nyagrodha tree, cut it open, and tell him what he sees. "Seeds, smaller than tiny," says Shvetaketu. "Cut one open," says his father. "What do you see now?" "Nothing at all," the young man replies. And then comes the teaching: "My son, that subtle essence which you cannot see—from that very essence this great nyagrodha tree arises. Believe me, my son, that which is the subtle essence—in it all that exists has its Self. That is the Real. That is the Self. That art thou, Shvetaketu."

Tat Tvam Asi—Thou Art That. In four Sanskrit words, one of the most radical propositions ever offered to a human being: your innermost identity is none other than the ground of all existence.

**What Are the Upanishads?**

The Upanishads are a collection of philosophical and contemplative texts that form the final portion of the Vedas—the ancient scriptural foundation of Hinduism. The word Upanishad traditionally means "sitting down near"—the image of a student drawing close to a teacher to receive instruction not from books, but from direct transmission of realized wisdom. Over one hundred Upanishads exist, but around twelve to fifteen are considered the principal ones, including the Chandogya, Brihadaranyaka, Mandukya, Kena, and Katha Upanishads.

Composed roughly between 1500 and 500 BCE—though scholars debate the exact dates—the Upanishads represent a profound turning point in Indian religious thought. The earlier Vedic period was largely concerned with elaborate rituals, sacrifices, and the maintenance of cosmic order through correct ceremony. The Upanishads moved decisively inward. They asked not "what rituals must be performed?" but "what is the nature of consciousness? What is the self? What is the relationship between the individual and the absolute?" In doing so, they inaugurated a tradition of philosophy as spiritual practice that has continued unbroken to the present day.

**Atman: The True Self**

Central to Upanishadic teaching is the concept of Atman—often translated as "Self" with a capital S. Atman does not refer to your personality, your memories, your preferences, or your sense of being a particular person in a particular body. These are the products of identification with what the Upanishads call the koshas or sheaths—the body, the energy body, the mental body, the wisdom body—each one a layer obscuring the luminous awareness that lies at the very center.

Atman is pure consciousness: uncreated, undying, free of all qualities, the silent witness behind every thought, perception, and experience you have ever had. You have always been aware. Awareness itself has never changed, even as its contents—thoughts, sensations, emotions, circumstances—have changed endlessly. That unchanging awareness is Atman.

The Mandukya Upanishad offers one of the most precise analyses of Atman through its examination of the three states of consciousness: waking (jagrat), dreaming (svapna), and deep dreamless sleep (sushupti). In each state, who you are appears to change—you are active, then absorbed in dream imagery, then apparently unconscious. Yet the Mandukya identifies a fourth condition (turiya) that underlies and witnesses all three: pure, undivided awareness that is neither created in the waking state nor destroyed in sleep. This turiya is Atman.

**Brahman: The Ground of All Being**

If Atman is the innermost nature of the individual, Brahman is the ultimate nature of the cosmos. Brahman is infinite being, consciousness, and bliss (sat-chit-ananda)—not a personal God who created the universe from outside, but the living ground out of which the entire universe arises and into which it continually returns, the way waves arise from and subside back into the ocean.

The Brihadaranyaka Upanishad describes Brahman through a series of penetrating negations—neti, neti, "not this, not this"—because any concept or image we form of ultimate reality inevitably falls short. Brahman cannot be contained by any description, including all our descriptions of what is sacred, good, or divine. It is beyond all qualities (nirguna Brahman), and yet it is also manifest in every quality and form—every sound, color, sensation, and relationship is Brahman appearing in a particular shape.

**The Great Identity: Tat Tvam Asi**

The Upanishads contain four statements known as the Mahavakyas, or Great Sayings, each one a compressed expression of their deepest teaching. Among them, "Tat Tvam Asi" (Thou Art That) and "Aham Brahmasmi" (I am Brahman) stand out as particularly direct. They assert that Atman and Brahman are not two different things—the innermost self of the individual is identical to the ground of all existence.

This is not a metaphor. The Upanishads are not saying that you are like Brahman, or that you will eventually merge with Brahman, or that Brahman is somewhere within you. They are saying that you already are Brahman—that the appearance of separation between the individual and the infinite is the fundamental misunderstanding (avidya, or ignorance) that gives rise to all suffering. Liberation (moksha) is not the acquisition of something new but the recognition of what has always already been true.

**The Method: From Hearing to Being**

The Upanishadic tradition identifies three stages of the path toward this recognition. The first is Shravana—literally, "hearing." The student receives the teachings from an authentic teacher, studies the texts, and builds an intellectual understanding of what is being pointed at. This is necessary but not sufficient.

The second stage is Manana—"reflection" or "deep consideration." The student contemplates the teachings from every angle, raises doubts and questions, examines counterarguments, and works through the intellectual obstacles that prevent the teaching from landing fully. Serious students of the Upanishads have found that this stage can last years.

The third stage is Nididhyasana—"profound meditation" or "unbroken contemplation." The student rests in sustained awareness of the truth being pointed at, allowing the gap between intellectual understanding and direct recognition to dissolve. This is the stage where the teaching stops being an interesting idea and becomes a lived reality.

**Why the Upanishads Still Matter**

We live in an age of spectacular scientific achievement and unprecedented existential confusion. Depression, anxiety, and a sense of meaninglessness are among the defining conditions of modern life—not because we lack information or comfort, but because we have lost contact with the deeper dimension of our own nature.

The Upanishads do not offer social prescriptions or political programs. They offer something stranger and more fundamental: an invitation to inquire into the actual nature of the self that is having every experience you will ever have. What is aware right now? Can awareness itself be found to have a boundary? Can it be damaged or destroyed?

These are not merely philosophical puzzles. They are doorways. And three thousand years of sincere practitioners have found that stepping through them—even partially, even provisionally—begins to change everything about how life feels from the inside.'
where title = 'The Upanishads: A Gentle Introduction';

update public.learn_articles
set content = 'When most people in the modern world think of yoga, they picture a sunlit studio, a rubber mat, and a sequence of postures flowing to carefully curated music. This is yoga as it has been transmitted into global culture—and there is genuine value in it. Physical health, stress reduction, and a taste of presence are real gifts. But to reduce yoga to its physical dimension is a bit like describing the ocean by pointing to the foam at its surface. Beneath the postures lies an entire universe: a philosophy of liberation, a detailed map of the human being, and a technology for self-transcendence that has been refined over thousands of years.

**The Yoga Sutras of Patanjali**

The most systematic exposition of classical yoga philosophy comes from the Yoga Sutras, a text attributed to the sage Patanjali and composed somewhere between 400 BCE and 400 CE. The Sutras are extraordinarily concise—196 aphorisms, some only a few words long—and have generated a vast literature of commentary across the centuries. Patanjali defines yoga in the second sutra with elegant economy: "Yoga is the cessation of the modifications of the mind." (Yogas chitta vritti nirodhah.) Not postures. Not breathing exercises. Not even spiritual experience. The stilling of the restless, constantly chattering mind—this is the goal.

When the mind becomes still, Patanjali says, the seer abides in its own nature. In other words: when the turbulence of thought quiets, what remains is pure awareness—your true self, prior to all the stories, roles, desires, and fears you have mistaken for yourself.

**The Eight Limbs: A Complete Path**

To arrive at this stillness, Patanjali describes eight interconnected practices known as the Ashtanga, or Eight Limbs of Yoga. These are not eight separate paths to choose among—they are eight dimensions of a single integrated practice, working together to purify body, energy, and mind in preparation for the deepest states of meditation.

*Yama* and *Niyama* form the ethical and personal foundation of the entire path, and their placement first is significant. Without a certain degree of moral integrity, the mind remains too turbulent for genuine spiritual development. The five Yamas are restraints in how we relate to the world: Ahimsa (non-harming), Satya (truthfulness), Asteya (non-stealing), Brahmacharya (right use of vital energy), and Aparigraha (non-grasping). The five Niyamas are personal observances: Saucha (purity), Santosha (contentment), Tapas (disciplined effort), Svadhyaya (self-study), and Ishvara Pranidhana (surrender to the divine). Together, they describe a way of living that progressively reduces the turbulence of fear, desire, and self-deception.

*Asana*, the third limb, is what most modern practitioners identify as yoga. In the context of Patanjali''s system, postures serve a specific purpose: to create a body that can sit comfortably and steadily in meditation for extended periods. The Sutras offer only one sutra on asana: "Sthira sukham asanam"—the posture should be stable and comfortable. The emphasis is not on flexibility, aesthetics, or physical achievement but on cultivating a quality of relaxed alertness in the body that becomes the foundation for inner work.

*Pranayama* is the conscious regulation of prana—the subtle life force that animates the body—through the vehicle of the breath. The ancient yogis understood that breath and mind are intimately connected: when the breath is irregular and erratic, the mind is agitated; when the breath becomes slow, deep, and rhythmic, the mind naturally settles. Pranayama practices include various ratios of inhalation, retention, and exhalation, as well as specific breathing patterns that affect the subtle energy body in precise ways.

*Pratyahara* is described as the withdrawal of the senses from their objects—turning awareness inward. In ordinary consciousness, awareness flows continuously outward through the senses, chasing sights, sounds, tastes, and sensations. Pratyahara reverses this direction. Rather than forcibly blocking the senses, it involves training the attention to remain absorbed in the inner dimension even when sensory input is present. This is often experienced during deep meditation as a natural withdrawal—sounds continue but cease to pull the mind outward.

*Dharana* means concentrated attention—holding the mind steadily on a single object: the breath, a visualization, a mantra, a flame, a philosophical concept. Most of what is taught as "meditation" in contemporary settings actually corresponds to dharana—the effortful application of attention. Like a student practicing a difficult piece of music, there is still effort involved in maintaining the focus.

*Dhyana* is the next stage—usually translated as meditation—and it refers to the effortless, unbroken flow of awareness toward the chosen object. The difference between dharana and dhyana is like the difference between pouring water from a cup (intermittent, punctuated by effort) and a continuous flow of oil. The meditator and the meditation have not yet merged, but the practice is becoming increasingly natural and self-sustaining.

*Samadhi* is the final limb—a state of absorption so complete that the distinction between the meditator, the act of meditating, and the object of meditation dissolves. Patanjali describes many gradations of samadhi, from states in which thought-forms remain to states of pure, object-free awareness. In the deepest samadhi, the individual mind temporarily ceases to be individual—it merges with its object completely. This is not unconsciousness; it is consciousness at a pitch of clarity and wholeness that everyday life rarely approaches.

**The Philosophy Behind the Practice**

Patanjali''s system assumes a metaphysical framework called Samkhya, which distinguishes between Purusha (pure consciousness, the witness) and Prakriti (matter, including the body and mind). The root of suffering, in this view, is the confusion between these two—mistaking the mind and body for who you truly are. Through yoga practice, this confusion is gradually dissolved, and the Purusha is seen to be eternally free, untouched by the changes of the material world. Liberation (Kaivalya—aloneness or independence) is the recognition of consciousness as fundamentally separate from and uncontaminated by the world of matter.

This philosophy intersects with Vedanta in important ways, though they have different metaphysical assumptions. Together, they represent the philosophical backbone of the Indian understanding of mind, consciousness, and liberation.

**Yoga as a Living Tradition**

Yoga in India has never been merely theoretical. The tradition emphasizes direct experience under the guidance of a realized teacher (guru). The guru-disciple relationship has historically been the vessel through which the deepest dimensions of yoga are transmitted—not through texts alone, but through the influence of a living presence that has itself traversed the inner landscape being mapped.

In the contemporary world, those pursuing yoga beyond its physical dimension will find an enormous wealth of resources—from the classical texts themselves to the teachings of modern masters like Swami Vivekananda, Sri Aurobindo, Ramana Maharshi, and many others who have brought these ancient practices into the living present.

The important thing to understand is that yoga is not a product and not a lifestyle. It is a path—serious, demanding, and extraordinarily rewarding—toward the direct recognition of who you truly are, beyond body, beyond mind, beyond all the identities and stories that constitute ordinary life. Every genuine practice of yoga, whether physical or contemplative, is a step on that path.'
where title = 'Yoga Philosophy Beyond Postures';

update public.learn_articles
set content = 'There is a moment, familiar to anyone who has sat in a room where sacred chanting is taking place, when something shifts. The sound gathers, the mind quiets without being asked to, and for a few seconds—or perhaps much longer—the usual background noise of thought and worry falls away. Something in you settles. This is not imagination. It is not sentiment. It is the effect of sacred sound on consciousness, and it has been understood and cultivated in Hindu and Buddhist traditions for thousands of years.

**The Ancient Science of Sacred Sound**

In the Indian philosophical tradition, sound is not merely vibration in air. It is a fundamental dimension of reality itself. The universe is understood to be an expression of primordial sound—the cosmic Om that underlies all phenomena. This understanding is not metaphorical but experiential: sages and yogis who had developed extraordinary sensitivity through long meditation reported directly perceiving the vibrational nature of reality, and their insights were systematized into an elaborate science of sacred sound that includes the mantras, chants, hymns, and prayers still used today.

The word mantra comes from two Sanskrit roots: manas (mind) and tra (instrument, or that which protects). A mantra is an instrument of the mind—a sound or group of sounds used deliberately to direct and purify consciousness. Unlike ordinary words, which convey meaning only through convention and interpretation, mantras are understood to carry intrinsic power in their sound—not in their translation.

**How Mantras Work**

On the most immediate level, a mantra works simply by giving the mind something to do. The mind in its untrained state tends to wander restlessly through past regrets and future anxieties. Repetition of a mantra—especially quiet, interior repetition—provides a focal point that gradually steadies the mental stream. This is the same basic principle underlying any meditation technique, but mantra has particular advantages: the repetition creates a rhythm, and rhythm is one of the most powerful organizers of awareness that human beings have ever discovered.

At a subtler level, Sanskrit mantras in particular are understood to work through the specific vibrational qualities of their sounds. Sanskrit is a language in which the sounds correspond with extraordinary precision to particular qualities of energy and consciousness. The sound of Om, for example, encompasses within its three phonemes (A-U-M) the full arc of creation, preservation, and dissolution—waking, dreaming, and deep sleep—and its resonance in the body and mind is direct and palpable.

The repetition of a mantra also works through what Indian philosophy calls samskara—the grooves or impressions left in consciousness by repeated experience. Just as walking frequently along a path through a field eventually creates a clear trail, repeating a mantra gradually creates a deep impression in the mind. Over months and years, the mantra begins to arise spontaneously in moments of stress, transition, or quiet—not because you are forcing it, but because the mind has been trained to return there naturally.

**Japa: The Practice of Mantra Repetition**

Japa means the repetitive recitation of a mantra, and it is one of the most universal spiritual practices in the Hindu tradition. The Bhagavad Gita identifies japa as the highest of all yajnas (sacred offerings): "Among yajnas I am japa-yajna." (10.25)

Traditional japa is performed with a mala—a set of 108 beads, similar to rosary beads. One bead is passed through the fingers with each repetition of the mantra. The number 108 is itself considered sacred across Hindu and Buddhist traditions, appearing in the number of Upanishads, the names of the divine, the distance between the earth and sun measured in solar diameters, and many other contexts that suggest an underlying harmonic ordering of reality.

Japa can be performed in three modes: Vaikhari japa involves audible chanting, using the full power of speech and breath. Upamshu japa is whispered repetition, more internal than audible chant. Manasika japa—mental japa—is entirely silent repetition within the mind, considered the most refined and most powerful form. Beginners often start with audible chanting and move progressively inward as the practice deepens.

**Kirtan and Bhajan: Chanting as Devotion**

Beyond the individual practice of japa, the traditions of kirtan and bhajan offer chanting as a communal, devotional practice. Kirtan is call-and-response chanting—usually the names and attributes of the divine—and bhajan is devotional song. Both are central practices in the Bhakti (devotion) path of Hinduism, which understands love and surrender as the most direct routes to the divine.

There is something remarkable about group chanting that individual practice cannot fully replicate. When many voices align on the same syllables, breathing together, the individual sense of separation softens. Walls between people become permeable. The collective sound creates an atmosphere—a field—in which states of consciousness become available that are difficult to access alone. This is why kirtan has been described by participants across cultures and centuries in almost identical terms: a sense of joy that is impersonal, a love that has no object, a peace that arrives uninvited.

**Buddhist Chanting and Mantra**

Buddhist traditions have their own extensive practices of sacred sound. In Tibetan Buddhism, mantra is one of the three pillars of tantric practice alongside visualization and mudra (sacred gesture). The mantra Om Mani Padme Hum—associated with Avalokiteshvara, the bodhisattva of compassion—is perhaps the most widely chanted mantra in the world. Each of its six syllables is understood to purify one of the six realms of samsara and cultivate one of the six perfections.

Zen and Theravada traditions include chanting of sutras and liturgical texts, the repetition of which in monastic contexts serves both as a form of meditation and as a way of imprinting the Buddha''s teachings on consciousness at a deep level. The sound of chanting in a monastery, sustained by many voices over many hours, creates conditions for states of clarity and stillness that would take much longer to access through individual sitting practice alone.

**Beginning a Mantra Practice**

If you are drawn to mantra practice, the first step is simply to choose a mantra and begin. For those with a Hindu orientation, Om, So Hum ("I am That"), or the Gayatri Mantra are excellent starting points. For those with a Buddhist orientation, Om Mani Padme Hum or a refuge chant may feel more natural. Some teachers emphasize receiving a mantra from an authorized teacher in a formal initiation—this is traditional and carries real value, but it is not essential for a sincere beginner.

Begin with 10-15 minutes of daily japa. Sit comfortably, keep your spine upright, hold your mala if you have one, and repeat your mantra with as much presence and sincerity as you can. Do not evaluate the practice after each session by how you felt. The work of mantra happens largely beneath the threshold of conscious awareness, and its fruits become visible over months and years, not days.

What you will likely notice first is that the practice creates a small but reliable island of stillness in your day. Over time, you may find the mantra arising spontaneously in difficult moments, offering a point of return. Over longer periods, the vibration of the mantra begins to color consciousness itself—a gradual brightening, a steady opening toward what the tradition calls the ground of being, or simply, peace.'
where title = 'Mantra and Chanting: Why It Works';

update public.learn_articles
set content = 'In the thirteenth century, a Japanese monk named Dogen returned from China after years of study and was asked what he had brought back. He said: "A soft and flexible heart." This answer—unexpected from someone who had crossed oceans in pursuit of the highest teachings—is a perfect point of entry into Zen, because Zen is fundamentally not about the acquisition of special knowledge or extraordinary experience. It is about seeing through the accumulated hardness of our habits of mind and recovering the natural openness and wonder that are already present.

**What Is Zen?**

Zen is a school of Mahayana Buddhism that traces its origins to the legendary encounter between the Indian monk Bodhidharma and the Chinese Emperor Wu in the sixth century CE. When the Emperor asked how much merit he had accumulated through his generous support of Buddhist monasteries, Bodhidharma replied: "No merit whatsoever." When the Emperor asked what the highest truth of Buddhism is, Bodhidharma answered: "Vast emptiness, nothing holy." And when the Emperor asked who this man was who stood before him defying all his expectations, Bodhidharma said: "I do not know."

This exchange encodes the entire spirit of Zen. It will not tell you what you want to hear. It will not offer comfortable answers or affirm your existing ideas about what is sacred. Instead, it points—bluntly, sometimes shockingly—directly at present reality, stripped of all conceptual overlay.

The word Zen is the Japanese pronunciation of the Chinese "Chan," which in turn is the Chinese rendering of the Sanskrit "Dhyana"—meditation. At its heart, Zen is a meditation tradition. But it approaches meditation and the whole question of awakening with a distinctive attitude: suspicious of intellectual elaboration, impatient with spiritual ambition, and ruthlessly focused on direct experience in this very moment.

**Shoshin: Beginner''s Mind**

In 1970, the Zen teacher Shunryu Suzuki published a small book called "Zen Mind, Beginner''s Mind," and its opening line became one of the most quoted statements in modern spirituality: "In the beginner''s mind there are many possibilities, but in the expert''s mind there are few."

Shoshin—beginner''s mind—is a quality of approach, not a stage of experience. It means coming to each moment without the filters of accumulated opinion, preference, and judgment. The expert arrives at a situation and immediately knows what it is, how it fits into already-established categories, and what should be done with it. The beginner simply looks, without needing the looking to immediately produce a conclusion.

As a spiritual quality, beginner''s mind is extraordinarily difficult to cultivate precisely because the human mind is so brilliantly efficient at categorization. We stop really seeing things the moment we have named and filed them. We stop really listening to people the moment we have decided we know who they are. We stop really experiencing the present moment the moment we have decided it is essentially the same as previous moments we have already processed.

Zen practice—particularly long periods of silent sitting—gradually loosens the grip of these mental habits. When everything goes quiet enough, the world reveals itself to be strange and immediate and inexhaustible in ways that the categorizing mind can never fully capture.

**Zazen: Just Sitting**

The central practice of Zen is zazen—a Japanese term meaning simply "seated meditation." But zazen as understood within the Soto school of Zen (the lineage of Dogen) is not meditation in the ordinary sense of working toward a goal or systematically cultivating a particular state. It is what Dogen called "shikantaza"—just sitting. Not sitting in order to achieve enlightenment, not sitting to calm the mind as a means to some other end, but sitting as a complete expression of awakening in itself.

This is a subtle but crucial distinction. Most meditation practices treat the sitting as a technique and enlightenment as the hoped-for result. Dogen''s approach dissolves this structure: the practice is the goal; the sitting is itself the expression of Buddha-nature. "To study the Buddha Way is to study the self. To study the self is to forget the self. To forget the self is to be enlightened by all things."

In zazen, one sits upright—ideally in full or half-lotus posture, though a chair is perfectly acceptable—with the gaze lowered to about 45 degrees, eyes slightly open. The hands form a specific mudra (cosmic mudra): left hand resting in the right, thumbs lightly touching to form an oval. Thoughts are allowed to arise and pass without being engaged or suppressed. There is no specific object of concentration, no mantra, no visualization. Just sitting, just breathing, just this.

**The Koan: A Sword That Kills Thought**

The Rinzai school of Zen developed a distinctive approach to awakening through the use of koans—paradoxical questions or statements assigned by a teacher to a student for contemplative investigation. The koan is not a riddle to be solved by thinking. It is a device that short-circuits the conceptual mind, pushing it to its limits and, when the effort is total, cracking it open into direct insight.

The most famous koan is "What is the sound of one hand clapping?" Others include "What was your face before your parents were born?" and "Does a dog have Buddha nature?" (To which the legendary master Zhaozhou answered: "Mu"—nothing, no.)

The student presents themselves before the teacher in a brief, intense private interview (dokusan or sanzen) and offers their response to the koan. An intellectual response is always rejected. The teacher is not looking for a clever answer but for evidence of direct insight—a response that comes not from the thinking mind but from somewhere deeper. Students sometimes work on a single koan for months or years before the breakthrough comes. When it does, the experience is described as a complete overthrow of the ordinary way of perceiving—a sudden dropping away of the imagined boundary between self and world.

**Everyday Life as Practice**

One of Zen''s most radical and practically important teachings is that the meditation hall is not the only—or even the primary—place where practice happens. The great Tang Dynasty master Baizhang, when asked what was the nature of spiritual practice, replied simply: "When hungry, eat. When tired, sleep." This is not permission for spiritual laziness. It is a description of the difficulty of being fully present even in the simplest activities.

When we eat, we are rarely just eating. We are planning, worrying, scrolling, arguing in our heads—using the eating body as a kind of ambulatory processing unit for the stream of mental commentary that constitutes most of ordinary life. To simply eat—to taste each bite fully, to feel the texture, to notice hunger''s easing—is actually quite difficult. It requires the quality of attention that formal meditation practice develops.

In Zen monasteries, this is made explicit through intensive training periods (sesshins) in which all daily activities—cooking, cleaning, working in the garden, eating—are performed with the same careful attention as zazen. The whole of life becomes practice. There is nowhere to hide from the quality of your presence.

**Why Zen Now?**

We live in a time of extraordinary distraction. The average person checks their phone over 90 times a day. Attention is the resource that every platform, application, and notification is engineered to capture and monetize. And quietly, the capacity for sustained, voluntary attention—which is the foundation of any kind of genuine depth, whether in relationships, creative work, or spiritual life—is being diminished.

Zen does not offer a ten-step program or a set of beliefs that will make life more comfortable. What it offers is more austere and more precious: an invitation back to the raw, immediate, unmediated experience of being alive in this moment. No backstory required. No spiritual credentials. Just this breath, this sensation, this fleeting and irreplaceable now.

The thirteenth-century master Dogen wrote: "For this reason, do not be concerned with whether enlightenment is near or far off. Do not be concerned with whether you are clever or dull. Just wholeheartedly sit in meditation. This is what is essential."

That is still the invitation. Sit down. Be here. Begin.'
where title = 'Zen Buddhism and Beginner''s Mind';
